messages.content:
Creating a simple webpage that allows you to play a MIDI file is possible, but since I cannot access external links, I'll provide you with a complete HTML template. You can modify the MIDI file path in the code to match the sounds you would like to play and then run this HTML in your browser.

Hereâ€™s a self-contained HTML file with embedded CSS and JavaScript:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>MIDI Player</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
            text-align: center;
            padding: 50px;
        }

        h1 {
            color: #333;
        }

        button {
            background-color: #007BFF;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            padding: 10px 20px;
            text-align: center;
            text-decoration: none;
            display: inline-block;
            font-size: 16px;
            margin: 4px 2px;
            cursor: pointer;
            border-radius: 5px;
        }

        button:hover {
            background-color: #0056b3;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>MIDI File Player</h1>
    <button id="play-btn">Play MIDI</button>
    <script src="https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/MidiPlayerJS/0.2.0/midi.player.min.js"></script>
    <script>
        const player = new MidiPlayer.Player();

        player.loadFile("your-midi-file.mid"); // Change this to your MIDI file path

        document.getElementById('play-btn').addEventListener('click', function() {
            if (player.isPlaying()) {
                player.pause();
                this.textContent = 'Play MIDI';
            } else {
                player.play();
                this.textContent = 'Pause MIDI';
            }
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Instructions:
1. Replace `"your-midi-file.mid"` with the correct path to your MIDI file.
2. Save the code into an HTML file (e.g., `midi_player.html`).
3. Open the file in a web browser.

### Note:
- Ensure that the MIDI file you want to play is accessible from the same directory as your HTML file or provide the correct path if located elsewhere.
- The MIDI file must be compatible with web MIDI player libraries, so ensure it is correctly formatted.
- The MIDI Player library used in this example (MidiPlayerJS) is included via CDN, so there's no need to download it.
